## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design data-sharing with masking, time-bounded access, and auditing.

## Key Concepts
- Data sharing lifecycle: SHARE, CONSUMER, future objects
- Masking policies and secure views for PII
- Time-bound access via scheduled tasks and governance logs
- Auditing using ACCOUNT_USAGE views

## Code Example
```sql
-- Part 1: share setup
CREATE SHARE partner_share; GRANT USAGE ON DATABASE PROD TO SHARE partner_share;
GRANT SELECT ON ALL TABLES IN SCHEMA PROD.PUBLIC TO SHARE partner_share;
-- Part 2: masking and view
CREATE MASKING POLICY email_mask AS (e STRING) RETURNS STRING -> CASE WHEN CURRENT_ROLE() IN ('PARTNER') THEN 'REDACTED' ELSE e END;
ALTER TABLE PROD.PUBLIC.USERS ALTER COLUMN email SET MASKING POLICY email_mask;
CREATE VIEW PROD.PUBLIC.USERS_VIEW AS SELECT id, name, email FROM PROD.PUBLIC.USERS;
GRANT SELECT ON VIEW PROD.PUBLIC.USERS_VIEW TO SHARE partner_share;
-- Part 3: revoke and audit
CREATE TASK revoke_shares WAREHOUSE WH_SVC SCHEDULE 'USING CRON 0 0 * * *' AS CALL SYS$REVOKE_EXPIRED_SHARES();
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test masking across multiple partner roles?
- How would you monitor and alert on unexpected access events?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to design an end-to-end Snowflake ELT for semi-structured logs, including external stages, staging vs. target tables, and simple QC/alerting.

## Key Concepts

- External stages and JSON formats
- Staging vs. target tables
- COPY INTO and data transformation
- TASK scheduling and QC views
- Simple alerting pattern

## Code Example

```sql
CREATE FILE FORMAT jsonfmt TYPE=JSON;
CREATE STAGE s3_logs URL='s3://logs-bucket/app-logs/';
CREATE TABLE LOGS_STG(timestamp_str STRING, user_id STRING, event_type STRING, payload VARIANT);
CREATE TABLE LOGS(timestamp_ntz TIMESTAMP_NTZ, user_id STRING, event_type STRING, payload VARIANT);
COPY INTO LOGS_STG FROM @s3_logs PATTERN='.*app_log.json' FILE_FORMAT=(FORMAT_NAME='jsonfmt');
INSERT INTO LOGS SELECT to_timestamp_ntz(timestamp_str), user_id, event_type, payload FROM LOGS_STG;
CREATE VIEW LOGS_QC AS SELECT date_trunc('DAY', timestamp_ntz) day, COUNT(DISTINCT user_id) users, COUNT(*) events FROM LOGS GROUP BY 1;
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you handle schema drift in JSON payloads?
- How would you adjust the pipeline for new fields or partitions?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests cross‑account sharing, row filtering, masking, and auditable usage in Snowflake.

## Key Concepts
- Secure Data Sharing across accounts
- SECURE VIEWs with row-level access
- Masking policies for PII
- Query auditing via QUERY_HISTORY and usage logs
- Cost/complexity trade-offs in view-based filtering

## Code Example
```sql
-- Provider side (simplified)
CREATE SHARE SHARED_SALES;
GRANT USAGE ON DATABASE RAW TO SHARE SHARED_SALES;
GRANT SELECT ON ALL TABLES IN SCHEMA RAW.SALES TO SHARE SHARED_SALES;
ALTER SHARE SHARED_SALES ADD TABLE RAW.SALES;

-- Consumer side (simplified)
CREATE DATABASE SHARED_SALES_DB FROM SHARE PROVIDER.ACCOUNT.SHARED_SALES;

CREATE MASKING POLICY mp_customer_id AS (val STRING) RETURNS STRING ->
  CASE WHEN CURRENT_ROLE() = 'CONSUMER_ROLE' THEN 'REDACTED' ELSE val END;
ALTER TABLE RAW.SALES ALTER COLUMN customer_id SET MASKING POLICY mp_customer_id;

-- Region-aware view (region context assumed via session variable)
SET REGION_CONTEXT = 'NA';
CREATE OR REPLACE SECURE VIEW SHARED_SALES_DB.V_SALES_REGION_MASK AS
SELECT sale_id, amount, sale_ts, region, customer_id
FROM RAW.SALES
WHERE region = REGION_CONTEXT;
```

